Routing, how packets find their destination.

When your machine wants to send a packet to some address out on the internet, the kernel consults its routing table to decide two things: which interface to send the packet through, and which next hop to hand it to. A routing table is essentially a list of rules of the form, if the destination matches this network, use this gateway by way of this interface. When several rules could match, the kernel always picks the most specific one.

To see your routes you run i-p route, with a separate command for version-six routes. A typical table has just two lines. The first begins with the word default and names a gateway and an interface; this is the default gateway, the catch-all rule that says, for anything that does not match another entry, send it to the router. The second line describes your local network directly attached to an interface, with no gateway needed because those machines are reachable directly, and it also shows the source address your packets will carry. Most machines have exactly these two rules: the local network is reachable directly, and everything else goes through the gateway. More elaborate setups, with v-p-ns or servers on several networks, simply add more rules.

You can manipulate routes by hand with i-p route add to create one, i-p route del to remove one, and i-p route change to alter the default gateway, though as before these changes are temporary and need to be set in your network configuration to persist. And there is one wonderfully useful debugging command: i-p route get, followed by a destination address, tells you exactly which interface and gateway a packet to that address would use. It answers the question, is my traffic actually going where I think it is, which comes up constantly when something is not working.
